				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\rm{ratio}}=\frac{S(T)/{S}_{{\rm{\max }}}}{L(T)/{L}_{{\rm{\max }}}}$$\end{document}It can be inferred from Fig. 1a that the entropy content in radiation, i.e. the ratio, increases monotonically with wavelength. At certain point, the ratio becomes the unity, and beyond that point, the content of entropy in radiation increases: the entropy content is lower than the unity for high energy photons, and rapidly increases in the infrared.

